cs.HC, cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.CYBER, cs.CV 

This paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) category as it deals with emotion recognition from biometrics, which is relevant to a wide range of application domains, including healthcare. 

It is also likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category as the authors report achieving state-of-the-art classification performance for both valence and arousal, which suggests the use of machine learning techniques. 

The Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) category is also a possibility as EEG and EMG sensors are used, which are related to neural activity. 

The Cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) category is a possibility as the authors mention the use of GSR sensors, which are related to detecting changes in skin conductance, a measure of physiological arousal that can be used to detect stress or anxiety. 

Finally, the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) category is a possibility as the authors may have used image processing techniques to analyze the data collected from the sensors.
